25","1236":"1236","1224":"1224","1212":"1212","1200":"1200","about 1236":"omkring 1236","about 1200":"omkring 1200","1208":"1208","about 1230":"omkring 1230","1317":"1317","Shunock, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England"},"nl":{"about 1200–":"circa 1200–Overleden","1200–Male":"1200–Overleden","1208–1325":"1208–1325","1212–Female":"1212–Overleden","1230–1325":"1230–1325","1236–Male":"1236–Overleden","1175–Male":"1175–Overleden","1184–Female":"1184–Overleden","1175":"1175","1230":"1230","1184":"1184","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1325":"1325","1236":"1236","1224":"1224","1212":"1212","1200":"1200","about 1236":"circa 1236","about 1200":"circa 1200","1208":"1208","about 1230":"circa 1230","1317":"1317","Shunock, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England"},"en":{"about 1200–":"about 1200–Deceased","1200–Male":"1200–Deceased","1208–1325":"1208–1325","1212–Female":"1212–Deceased","1230–1325":"1230–1325","1236–Male":"1236–Deceased","1175–Male":"1175–Deceased","1184–Female":"1184–Deceased","1175":"1175","1230":"1230","1184":"1184","1290":"1290","1315":"1315","1259":"1259","1215":"1215","1325":"1325","1236":"1236","1224":"1224","1212":"1212","1200":"1200","about 1236":"about 1236","about 1200":"about 1200","1208":"1208","about 1230":"about 1230","1317":"1317","Shunock, Cornwall, England":"Cornwall, England","Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England":"Ingoldsby, Lincolnshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Dawnay","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["Norman, English: locative name from one of the many places in northern France named from an alder grove (Old French  <i>aulnai</i>,  <i>aulnoi</i>, latinized as  <i>alnetum</i>), such as Annay (Pas-de-Calais), Aulnay (Aube, Marne, Calvados), Aulnois (Aisne), and Aunay (Calvados, Eure-et-Loire, Seine-et-Oise). With fused preposition, Anglo-Norman French  <i>d'Aunai</i> became  <i>Dawnay</i>,  <i>Dawney</i> and (with loss of the final syllable)  <i>Dawn</i>.   Laney   is another form of this surname with fused definite article.  See also  Dando  , from Anglo-Norman French  <i>d'Aunou</i>, with which  <i>d'Aunai</i> may sometimes have been confused."],"variants":[{"name":"Dawney","meanings":["Norman, English:  See  Dawnay  ."]},{"name":"Laney","meanings":["Irish: probably a shortened and altered form of   McElhinney  .","English and Irish: habitational name introduced by the Normans originally deriving from any of the many places in northern France called L'Aunai (from Latin <i>alnetum</i> ‘alder grove’). It may also have developed to   Delaney  .","Variant of   Laine   2, a surname of French origin."]},{"name":"Dawn","meanings":["English (Derbyshire and Nottinghamshire): of Norman origin, probably a clipped form of <b>Dawnay</b> or <b>Dawney</b> (compare   Dana  ), habitational names from one of the many places in northern France named for an alder grove (Old French <i>aulnai</i>, <i>aulnoi</i>, Latinized as <i>alnetum</i>). With fused preposition <i>d(e)</i>, Anglo-Norman <i>d'Aunai</i> became <i>Dawnay</i>, <i>Dawney</i> and (with loss of the final syllable) <i>Dawn</i>.   Laney   is another form of this surname with fused definite article. See also   Dando  , from Anglo-Norman <i>d'Aunou</i>, with which <i>d'Aunai</i> may sometimes have been confused.","English: from Middle English <i>Dawen</i>, a variant of   Dawes   with the weak declension genitival suffix <i>-(e)n</i> (Old English <i>-an</i>) instead of the standard Middle English <i>-es</i>. The usage is mainly restricted to West Midlands dialects of Middle English.","Americanized form of German   Daun  ."]},{"name":"Doney","meanings":["English (Cornwall): of uncertain origin. There is a Richard <i>Donowe</i> recorded in 1451-64 as a tenant in Manuels, Saint Columb Minor, whose surname appears to be a pet form of an unidentified personal name with the Cornish hypocoristic suffix <i>-ow</i>. Formally this might have become <i>Doney</i> but <i>Donowe</i> itself seems not to have survived, unless it was altered to   Downey  . However, there is no evidence to suggest any connection of this west Cornwall surname with <i>Doney</i> in central and east Cornwall (Bodmin and Quethiock). Alternatively, perhaps it is a variant of the Devon name   Downey  , and with the main vowel shortened and lowered, but evidence for this is lacking.","Americanized form of French Canadian   Daunais   or   Donais  ."]},{"name":"Dando","meanings":["English (of Norman origin): habitational name for someone from Aunou-le-Faucon in Orne, Normandy, with fused preposition. Aunou was named for an alder grove, from Latin <i>alnus</i> ‘alder’ + the Gaulish suffix <i>-avum</i>. In medieval England <i>d'Aunou</i> developed an intrusive <i>-d-</i>, giving <i>Dando</i>. The surname was sometimes confused with <i>d'Aunay</i> or <i>d'Auney</i> (see   Delaney  )."]}]},{"name":"Richard","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."],"variants":[{"name":"Rikert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]},{"name":"Rickert","meanings":["One of the most enduringly successful of the Old French personal names introduced into Britain by the Normans. It is of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>rīc</i> ‘power’ + <i>hard</i> ‘strong, hardy’. It has enjoyed continuous popularity in England from the Conquest to the present day, influenced by the fact that it was borne by three kings of England, in particular  Richard I  (  1157–99 ). He was king for only ten years (  1189–99 ), most of which he spent in warfare abroad, taking part in the Third Crusade and costing the people of England considerable sums in taxes. Nevertheless, he achieved the status of a folk hero, and was never in England long enough to disappoint popular faith in his goodness and justice. He was also Duke of Aquitaine and Normandy and Count of Anjou, fiefs which he held at a time of maximum English expansion in France. His exploits as a leader of the Third Crusade earned him the nickname ‘Coeur de Lion’ or ‘Lionheart’ and a permanent place in popular imagination, in which he was even more firmly enshrined by  Sir Walter Scott's  novel Ivanhoe (  1820 )."]}]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705187,"age":15,"year":"1215","julianDay":2164830,"title":"Magna Carta","description":"King John of England agreed to a charter of rights called the Magna Carta. The document was originally drafted by the Archbishop of Canterbury to establish peace between King John and a group of rebel barons. The Magna Carta was completed in 1215 and is now considered to be one of the greatest constitutional documents of all time.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/education/medieval/magna-carta/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Magna Carta","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705188,"age":24,"year":"1224","julianDay":2168117,"title":"France Declares War on England","description":"France declared war on England as Louis VIII of France attacked Poitou and northern Gascony.","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705189,"age":59,"year":"1259","julianDay":2180901,"title":"100 Years of Conflict Between England and France Ends","description":"Treaty of Paris was signed on December 4, 1259, which ended 100 years of conflict between England and France.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Treaty_of_Paris_(1259)","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Treaty of Paris 1259","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705190,"age":90,"year":"1290","julianDay":2192224,"title":"Jews Expelled From England","description":"After years of anti-Semitic behavior, King Edward I expelled Jews from England in 1290.","